ce:section.ce:para:
Neutralization of surface charge of the particles in presence of Pb2+ ions is suggested as the reason for particle coagulation. Along with this, it is to be noted that in presence of heavy metal ions, functional group bridging [35] is also reported for HA moieties, which also facilitates aggregation of carbon dots. A comparison of FTIR spectra of the systems provides a clear cut idea to this (Fig. 6
                        ). The IR band of symmetric COO-stretch at 1404 cm−1 for HA shifts to 1373 cm−1 for HA-Pb (II) complex, indicating interaction with metal ion. The difference between asymmetric and symmetric stretching vibrations (Δ) of carboxylate group can provide idea about the nature of bonding that the group makes with metals [36].The difference between anti-symmetric and symmetric stretching vibrations (Δ) between the two systems was 136 cm−1 for pure carbon dots, the value of which shifted to 185 cm−1 after the addition of Pb2+. There is an increase in Δ value. A decrease in delta shows chelate formation (bi-dentate, metal bound to both the oxygen atoms of the carboxyl group), while an increase in the said value predicts mono-dentate bridge formation. Here the delta value increased, indicating mono-dentate (one oxygen from carboxylic interacts with metal) binding, leading to bridging between the particles resulting aggregation. The two representations of bridging are shown in Fig. 7
                        , as proposed by Jerzykiewicz et al., based on the shift in FTIR bands [37]. Among these two pictorial representations corresponding to bridging, the second model (model shown below in the Fig. 7)is more probable, as Pb (II) binding preferably decreases the symmetric COO- stretching vibrations. Hence neutralization of charge on carboxylate groups is assumed to be the reason behind the aggregate formation. Similar mono-dentate bridging model was reported by Orsetti et al. also [36].
